This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) category as it presents a new regularization method for semantic tissue segmentation in histopathological images using a fully convolutional network. The paper also proposes a new embedding that generates a multi-channel output image by superimposing an original input image on its segmentation map, which is a common technique used in computer vision. Additionally, the paper uses generative adversarial networks (GANs) for image-to-image translations, which is a popular technique in computer vision. 

The paper also involves machine learning (cs.LG) as it proposes a new method that combines supervised and unsupervised learning objectives through a single generative model. The paper uses a conditional GAN to learn the united task of semantic segmentation and image reconstruction. 

The paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) category as it proposes a new method that combines multiple objectives to improve the performance of a neural network. 

The paper involves neural networks (cs.NE) as it uses a fully convolutional network and a conditional GAN for image-to-image translations. 

Finally, the paper may belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) category as it deals with histopathological images, which are a type of medical image.
